). The hypandrium is narrow and a bit wider in the middle ( Figs. 31 , 40). The epiproct ( Figs. 30, 32 ) is small, oval-shaped, narrow, and 2.2 times longer than it is wide. The setae are widely spaced. The hypoproct ( Figs. 30, 32 ) is large, almost tongue shaped, wider in the middle, and the caudal part is almost hemicircular and densely haired. The setae on both parts are of the same length, rather short. The surstyli ( Figs. 30, 32 ) are almost 1.5 times as long as the epandrium, C-shaped from the lateral view, straight from the dorsal view, and subapically have 16–19 retinaculi, which gradually become shorter towards the top of surstylus. The retinaculi are apically frayed ( Figs. 32 , 43).
